1.transformed_text:
The plaintiffs, children under state care and placed in Illinois foster homes, filed this lawsuit on September 15, 1988, in the U.S. District Court for the Northern District of Illinois, against the Illinois Department of Children and Family Services (DCFS). Represented by the Office of the Cook County Public Guardian, the plaintiffs based their case on the Adoptive Assistance and Child Welfare Act of 1980. They argued that DCFS's practice of placing siblings in separate homes and denying them visits violated their First and Fourteenth Amendment rights.

In 1989, DCFS asked for a summary judgment. U.S. District Court Judge Ann C. Williams did not dismiss the First Amendment claim about the children's right to associate with their siblings, nor the Fourteenth Amendment substantive due process rights claims regarding the plaintiffs' liberty interest in their relationships with their siblings. However, the Judge did dismiss the claim based on the Adoptive Assistance and Child Welfare Act of 1980. *Aristotle P. v. Johnson*, 721 F. Supp. 1002 (N.D. Il. 1989).

In October 1989, Judge Williams approved the case as a class action for children in DCFS custody who were involved in neglect, dependency, or abuse cases, had not been placed with their siblings in foster homes, and had been denied regular, reasonable visits with their siblings. The parties discussed a possible settlement from 1990-1993. In December 1993, they proposed a consent decree. The following March, a notice of the class action went out to all children involved in abuse, neglect, or dependency cases in the Juvenile Court of Cook County. After a fairness hearing, Judge Williams approved the consent decree on March 11, 1994.

The decree included specific rules for child placement, permanency planning, mental health, education, health care, protective services, initial assessments of children, adequate food/shelter/clothing, caseload ratios, information systems, licensing, training, and quality assurance. The consent decree set minimum visitation rights for siblings who could not be placed together for clear reasons. DCFS must provide written notice to siblings when deciding they cannot be placed together or when changing a sibling's placement. Foster parents receive money for transportation when they transport children and supervise sibling visits. Agencies that contract with DCFS and do not follow the decree can be fined.

In February 1997, the parties jointly asked to extend the consent decree to 1999. The court extended parts of the consent decree several more times, especially the parts about sibling visitation. However, the rules about sibling placement ended in 2003 because the Department showed it was largely following those rules.

On March 8, 2014, the plaintiffs filed a request to again extend the sibling visitation rules of the decree and asked for other changes. The plaintiffs complained that DCFS had not shown enough proof that it was largely following the consent decree. They listed five main problems with DCFS's actions:

1) DCFS had completed only about a third of its total reviews for the two-year period from March 2012 through March 2014;
2) The reviews DCFS completed were faulty because they used biased cases, not randomly chosen ones;
3) DCFS used its own 75% standard to decide if it was largely compliant in reviewing a case;
4) DCFS left out cases that were not exceptions allowed by the decree; and
5) DCFS did not respond to the plaintiffs' request for a study of sibling visits using random cases from Cook County.

As a result, the plaintiffs asked the Court to extend the consent decree for two years and to do the following:

1) Order DCFS to provide all quality assurance reviews completed since March 2012;
2) Order DCFS to use a proven method or random selection in its quality assurance review process;
3) Order DCFS to use only the reasons specified in the consent decree to exclude cases;
4) Order that DCFS change its policy to allow fines based on quality assurance reviews; and
5) Order DCFS to follow the plaintiffs' request for information from December 18, 2013.

On February 23, 2015, Judge Charles R. Norgle, Sr., even though the defendant objected, approved the plaintiffs' request for a two-year extension and other changes.

On February 22, 2017, the plaintiffs again asked the court to extend the consent decree for two years. The plaintiffs raised many of the same concerns about DCFS's compliance that they had in their March 2014 request. Besides a two-year extension of the consent decree, the plaintiffs asked the court to order DCFS to hire an independent auditor to complete the remaining sibling visitation reviews.

After allowing DCFS several extensions to file its response to the plaintiffs' request to extend the consent decree, the court gave DCFS until November 13, 2018, to file its response. However, court records do not show any further action after the court's most recent extension. As of August 2020, court records do not show whether DCFS filed its response by the deadline.

2.transformed_text:
Children in Illinois foster care sued the Illinois Department of Children and Family Services (DCFS) in a federal court in Chicago on September 15, 1988. They were represented by the Cook County Public Guardian's office. Their case was based on a federal law called the Adoptive Assistance and Child Welfare Act of 1980, which aims to help states provide foster care and adoption services. They claimed DCFS's practice of placing brothers and sisters in different foster homes and not letting them visit each other violated their constitutional rights, specifically their First Amendment right to associate and their Fourteenth Amendment right to due process.

In 1989, DCFS asked the court to dismiss the case without a trial, a process known as seeking "summary judgment." U.S. District Court Judge Ann C. Williams allowed the claims about the children's First Amendment right to be with their siblings and their Fourteenth Amendment right to maintain those family relationships to continue. However, she dismissed the part of the lawsuit based on the Adoptive Assistance and Child Welfare Act of 1980.

In October 1989, Judge Williams allowed the case to proceed as a "class action." This meant it would represent a group of children in DCFS care who were part of neglect, dependency, or abuse cases, had not been placed with their siblings, and were not allowed regular visits with them. The two sides talked about a possible agreement from 1990 to 1993. In December 1993, they suggested a "consent decree" to the court. A consent decree is a legal agreement approved by a judge that settles a lawsuit without a full trial. The following March, a notice about the class action was sent to all children in abuse, neglect, or dependency cases in Cook County's Juvenile Court. After a hearing to ensure it was fair, Judge Williams approved the consent decree on March 11, 1994.

The decree set specific rules for how DCFS should place children, plan for their long-term care, and handle their mental health, education, health care, and safety. It also covered initial evaluations, basic needs like food and shelter, how many cases workers could handle, data systems, licensing, training, and quality checks. It also established minimum visitation rights for brothers and sisters who could not be placed in the same foster home for good reasons. DCFS had to tell siblings in writing when they couldn't be placed together or when a sibling's placement changed. Foster parents would get money for transportation when they took children to and supervised sibling visits. Agencies working with DCFS that failed to follow the decree could face fines.

In February 1997, both sides jointly asked to extend the consent decree until 1999. The court extended parts of the decree several more times, especially those dealing with sibling visits. However, the rules about placing siblings together ended in 2003 because DCFS showed it was mostly following them.

On March 8, 2014, the plaintiffs asked the court again to extend the sibling visitation rules of the decree and make other changes. They argued that DCFS had not provided enough evidence to prove it was largely following the agreement. They pointed out five main problems with DCFS's actions:

1) DCFS had finished only about a third of its required reviews for the two years between March 2012 and March 2014;
2) The reviews DCFS did were flawed because they used cases that weren't chosen randomly, leading to biased results;
3) DCFS used its own 75% standard to decide if it was mostly following the rules when reviewing a case;
4) DCFS excluded cases that the decree did not allow to be excluded; and
5) DCFS failed to respond to the plaintiffs' request for a study of sibling visits using randomly selected cases from Cook County.

Because of this, the plaintiffs asked the court to extend the consent decree for two years and to order DCFS to:

1) Provide all quality assurance reviews completed since March 2012;
2) Use a reliable method, like random selection, for its quality assurance reviews;
3) Exclude cases only for reasons specifically allowed by the consent decree;
4) Change its policy to allow fines based on quality assurance reviews; and
5) Comply with the plaintiffs' request for information from December 18, 2013.

On February 23, 2015, Judge Charles R. Norgle, Sr., approved the plaintiffs' request for a two-year extension and other changes, even though DCFS objected.

On February 22, 2017, the plaintiffs again asked the court to extend the consent decree for two years. They brought up many of the same concerns about DCFS's compliance that they had in their March 2014 request. Besides extending the decree for two years, the plaintiffs asked the court to order DCFS to hire an independent auditor to finish the remaining reviews of sibling visits.

After giving DCFS several extensions to respond to the plaintiffs' request, the court set a new deadline of November 13, 2018, for DCFS to file its answer. However, court records do not show any further action after that last extension. As of August 2020, it's unclear from court records whether DCFS ever filed its response by the deadline.
